<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Major rallies party against threat of Liberal Democrats:
Prime minister to visit regional activists in effort to restore morale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservatives are launching a sustained offensive against the Liberal
Democrats, whom they now believe pose the main threat to traditional Tory
strongholds in the south.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, will lead the fight with a visit to the
west country today to rebuild morale after the battering the Tories have
taken over the past year.
It will be the first in a series of meetings with party activists ahead of
the Conservative party conference in October.
Mr Major is to visit other regions this week, probably including the
Midlands and Scotland. His itinerary is being kept secret for security
reasons.
Switching targets from Labour to the Liberal Democrats, especially in the
south-west, is a recognition by Tory party strategists that they must win
back disaffected voters in those areas if they are to win the next general
election.
In July, the Liberals won a spectacular by-election victory in Christchurch
in Dorset, while at the local elections in May they took control of Cornwall
and Somerset county councils from the Tories, and became the largest single
party in Devon and Dorset.
Another disastrous performance in the European elections next June might put
Mr Major's leadership in jeopardy. The switch of focus from Labour, whom the
Tories believe are mired in their own difficulties, to the Liberal Democrats
is also designed to prevent that from happening.
The Conservative campaign will seek to portray Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal
Democrat leader, as an untrustworthy politician who tailors his arguments to
his audiences and so cannot be trusted to take a consistent line.
The campaign will also spell out elements of Liberal Democrat policy in
areas such as Europe and defence, which the government believes are least
likely to appeal to traditional Tory supporters - even when they are
disenchanted with their own party.
The initiative comes less than two weeks before the Liberal Democrats meet
at Torquay for their annual conference, at which they hope to build on their
recent electoral successes.
Sir Norman Fowler, the Tory party chairman, spent two days in the south-west
this week as part of his tour of local associations, talking to constituency
chairmen and their deputies.
Speaking in north Dorset yesterday, Sir Norman said: 'The Liberal party take
a supportive view of a federal superstate, a federal Europe, the kind of
Europe we stand against. That distinction is not recognised by the public,
and we want to underline it.'
Renewed efforts to drive home the contrast between the Liberal Democrats and
themselves over the European Community are important for the Tories, since
they will help to set the stage for the elections to the European parliament
next year.
The government is concerned about a possible strong vote for Mr Ashdown's
party in the European elections, which might lay the groundwork for a
successful general election campaign.
Only as the bitter divisions within the Tory party over Maastricht have
moved out of the political spotlight have Conservative strategists felt it
safe to focus on European policy.
Special responsibility for the campaign against the Liberal Democrats will
go to Mr Patrick Nicholls, a party vice-chairmen.
TUC reports, Page 10
Smith pledges, Page 20
</TEXT>
