<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 93 / Mercury steps up mobile phones battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CREATION of a mass consumer market for cellular phones came closer
yesterday with the launch of Mercury's One-2-One network.
One-2-One, the third national cellular network, offered free local calls in
the evenings and at weekends as the centrepiece of an aggressive Pounds 10m
campaign.
The network is available only in the London area, but it is planned to cover
most of the UK by early 1996. A joint venture between Cable and Wireless and
US West, One-2-One is a high-capacity digital network.
Lord Young, Cable and Wireless chairman, said the 'main target' of One-2-One
was British Telecommunications. But with peak-rate tariffs and rental and
handset prices several times higher than BT's, competition is likely to be
felt most by the existing mobile operators, Vodafone and Cellnet.
BT said One-2-One was not a replacement for fixed-line phones. Mr Ian Ash,
BT's marketing director, said: 'Apart from a marketing ploy for cheap-rate
local calls, every other call will cost markedly more than BT's'
Mr Terry Barwick, Vodafone's director of corporate affairs, said the company
would not react with further cuts. 'Competition has got to be seen to work.
If we reacted, we could kill them.'
One-2-One has spent about Pounds 150m on the first phase of its network, and
expects to be profitable within four to five years. Its focus on the private
consumer market is a new departure for the eight-year-old cellular industry,
most of whose 1.7m customers are business users.
Free off-peak local calls are available only on One-2-One's 'PersonalCall'
tariff, after 7pm on weekdays or at weekends. A Pounds 20 connection fee and
Pounds 12.50 monthly subscription are payable (excluding VAT). Calls before
7pm cost 25p a minute, off-peak national calls 10p.
A separate business tariff has a higher monthly subscription (Pounds 20) and
an 8p a minute charge for all off-peak calls, but a lower peak-rate charge
of 16p a minute. Handsets for the new digital network are retailing at
Pounds 250-Pounds 300.
The City views One-2-One as a serious challenger in the cellular market. Mr
Bryan Van Dussen, analyst at the Yankee Group, said: 'It changes the ball
game entirely. Until now Cellnet and Vodafone have stressed their national
coverage, but the special tariff changes play to Mercury's strength as a
local operator.'
Five years ago, the UK had fewer than 200,000 mobile subscribers. Analysts
expect the number to rise to more than 6m by 2000. The Telecommunications
Users Association said One-2-One marked 'a new era in mobile
communications'.
Growing warfare, Page 19
Observer, Page 19
Lex, Page 20
London stocks, Page 40
Mobile communications survey, Separate section
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
