<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Properties firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and TOM FORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A bright property sector was enlivened by recommendations fom Kleinwort
Benson and SG Warburg, as well as some positive weekend press comment. Among
those doing well, British Land rose 5 to 385p, as did Land Securities, to
663p, while MEPC added 9 at 496p.
Press speculation that Ladbroke Group was considering floating its property
division caused little interest in the market. While the company was said to
be denying the move to analysts, many said they believed that such a
development would eventually find its way on to the company's debt-cutting
agenda, although not until next year. Ladbroke shares climbed a half-penny
to 210p.
RTZ, the world's biggest mining group, firmed 3 to 735p in the registered
ahead of first-half results due on Thursday. The group is forecast to
announce profits of Pounds 170m to Pounds 200m, up to 25 per cent ahead of
last year's as a result of improved productivity, acquisitions and currency
gains.
Royal Bank of Scotland continued to receive support from a broker's buy
recommendation on Friday, adding 4 at 292p. National Westminster was
restrained by speculation of a large preference share issue, but analysts
were sceptical and added that it would have little impact on the ordinary
shares, which closed a penny firmer at 481p.
Oil group Burmah was held back as investors digested last week's results and
decided that they were slightly more disappointing than the headline figure
suggested. The shares slipped 4 1/2 to 773p xd.
In spite of the Labor Day closure of the US markets, Enterprise Oil was
bought by US institutions operating in London and rose 6 to 494p .
The majors, Shell Transport and BP, were restrained by a weaker oil price
and ended slightly easier on balance at 665p and 307p respectively.
Pharmaceuticals group Wellcome was held back by reports of a Japanese drug
found to be capable of inhibiting the death of cells infected by HIV, the
virus that causes Aids.
The drug will need to be tested in animals for at least two years before any
clinical trial can be considered so the drug is many years away from the
market. Wellcome is always vulnerable to negative sentiment from Aids
stories. The shares shed 9 at one stage and closed 5 off at 744p.
Glaxo improved 2 to 620p ahead of full-year results on Thursday, with volume
boosted by heavy activity in the traded options market. Analysts expect
about Pounds 1.66bn, up from Pounds 1.43bn in 1992, but there are some
worries that in the light of the new harsher climate for the drugs industry
the accompanying statement could encourage profit-taking.
Medeva advanced 5 to 123p xd as securities house Smith New Court repeated a
buy recommendation, arguing that the share price, which has halved since a
profits warning last month, was cheap. Also, word leaked out that French
owned SGST was preparing an enthusiastic piece of research.
Dealers pointed to a recommendation from a small broker aimed at private
clients as the reason behind strength in Enviromed, up 7 at 118p.
Whispers of a big rights issue ahead of Cadbury Schweppes' results on
Thursday were being heard. Analysts said that while such an event would not
be surprising, similar talk has been well aired in the past. The shares
gained 2 at 476p.
Shares in shipbuilder Vosper Thornycroft were in demand after it announced a
further order from Qatar to provide spares, maintenance and training for
four fast strike craft which it ordered from Vosper last year. They rose 12
to 674p.
Vague talk that GKN was taking a look at Westland, in which it has a stake,
was heard, although analysts dismissed suggestions of a takeover. GKN closed
at 488p xd and the latter put on 8 at 244p.
A positive annual meeting held by engineering group Siebe boosted the stock,
the shares gaining 9 to 541p.
Figures released at the weekend showing a sharp increase in UK car sales
boosted several stocks in the motor sector. These included distributor
Bletchley, where the shares jumped 25 to 335p, ahead of Friday's interim
figures; Dagenham Motor, which hardened 3 to 139p; and Pendragon, 5 better
at 283p.
Steel group ASW Holdings fell 10 to 214p after it reported interim figures
below market expectations, inspite of returning to profit. Half-time figures
came in at Pounds 1.5m against a loss of Pounds 2.1m last time. Brokers
moved to downgrade full-year expectations following the figures, with Smith
New Court reducing its forecast by Pounds 3m to Pounds 11m.
Conglomerate Suter cheered the market by reporting bumper profits and the
shares hardened 4 to 184p.
Birkby, the property and vehicle hire company, rose 6 to 190p and Cosalt,
the manufacturer and supplier, was lifted 13 to 130p. Dealers said a bear
squeeze was responsible for pushing both stocks higher. Birkby received
additional support from the property market's recent good run.
Elsewhere, food maufacturing issues were mostly positive, with Hoare Govett
advising clients to switch out of capital goods stocks and to go overweight
in the sector. Nervousness ahead of results today pulled down Hillsdown, off
3 at 165p.
Publisher Harrington Kilbride jumped 16 to 250p ahead of interim results
today. Meanwhile Haynes, the publisher of technical manuals, leapt 37 to
455p after a boost in profits to Pounds 3.95m and a confident statement from
the chairman.
</TEXT>
