FT  07 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Chairman of Linx resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHAIRMAN of Linx Printing Technologies, the maker of continuous ink-jet
printing equipment, has resigned after the company's poor full-year results,
making way for Mr Michael Moore, non-executive chairman of Tomkins, the
conglomerate.
Mr Moore was appointed as a non-executive director of Linx before the
company's flotation last October.
The shares, which floated at 130p, have been around yesterday's closing
price of 94p in recent weeks. They peaked at 220p in March, fell from about
180p to 120p after a profits warning in May and the resignation of Mr John
Shead, the sales and marketing director.
This spring, both Linx and its UK rival Domino Printing Sciences warned of
poor trading because of the recession and the market's maturity. Linx also
admitted to what Mr Harris called 'structural problems on the marketing
side'.
Linx full-year results in July showed pre-tax profits for the year to June
30 down by 13 per cent to Pounds 1.43m (Pounds 1.64m) on sales of Pounds
11.9m (Pounds 10.5m).
</TEXT>
