<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Intrum expands to Pounds 7.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTRUM Justitia, the debt collector, yesterday reported pre-tax profits up
from Pounds 6.81m to Pounds 7.47m in the six months to June 30, flattered by
the previous period's heavier interest payments and other charges.
Turnover rose to Pounds 41.7m (Pounds 41.6m) with the release of a provision
a year ago disguising an increase on continuing operations and acquisitions
from Pounds 40.3m to Pounds 41.7m. Operating profits fell to Pounds 7.82m
(Pounds 8.07m).
The company said that allowing for exceptional items and a change in the
treatment of goodwill, pre-tax profit rose 16.7 per cent, operating profit
was up 10 per cent and turnover grew 3.5 per cent.
Mr Bo Goranson, chief executive of the Netherlands-based but London-listed
company, said: 'We have produced a nice profit but we are in our own
recession. When normal companies go into recession they decrease their
business and the outcome at the end is that we get fewer debt collections.'
He added: 'But we see a light in the tunnel. We have already signs in the UK
that there is a recovery particularly for us, the increase in consumer
borrowing, the car industry picking up.'
The board declared an increased gross interim dividend of 1.1p (1p) out of
earnings per share of 5.2p (4.6p restated).
</TEXT>
