<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Thorn EMI warns on profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Thorn EMI fell 21p to 983p yesterday after a circular to
shareholders warned that profits from security and electronics would be no
greater this year than last and that the group's tax rate would increase.
Several analysts complained that the news came in what appeared to be a
routine letter to shareholders about the sale of the group's lighting
division. They said the announcement should have appeared on stock exchange
screens.
In the circular, posted to shareholders last Friday, Sir Colin Southgate,
chairman, said current year profits from the security and electronics
business would be around last year's level of Pounds 1.5m. The group
announced last month that it had failed to sell the defence side of its
electronics business to the General Electric Company.
Sir Colin added that the effect of recent disposals, including lighting,
meant that profits earned in the UK would be lower than last year. As a
result, the group would incur additional unrelieved advance corporation tax
and its overall tax rate would increase. He added that the music and rental
divisions had started the year well and their performance should be in line
with expectations.
Mr Mark Finnie of NatWest Securities said that he had still not received the
circular by the close of stock exchange business yesterday. He noted that SG
Warburg, the group's brokers, appeared to have received the notice in good
time. He said: 'It's very unlike Thorn EMI to have done this sort of thing.'
Mrs Julia Pennington of Barclays de Zoete Wedd had reduced Thorn's expected
full-year pre-tax profits after exceptional items to Pounds 345m from Pounds
370m.
Thorn said yesterday that it had lodged the circular with the stock exchange
last Friday and an announcement had been made that it was available for
inspection. The group said the comments in the circular on likely profits
this year were required under stock exchange rules. 'It is not an
announcement we would have made in the normal course of events,' the group
said.
</TEXT>
