<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Builders cautious on upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO of the UK's leading building materials and housebuilding groups reported
higher profits yesterday, but both urged caution in assessing the recovery.
Wilson Bowden, one of Britain's most successful housebuilders, said it sold
28 per cent more houses in the first half. Pre-tax profits rose to Pounds
16.8m, from Pounds 10.3m, with help from a pension surplus.
But Mr David Wilson, chairman and chief executive, said the group had yet to
see any evidence of house price rises and suggested that its higher volumes
in part reflected the group's success in increasing market share.
This year, with the total UK new housing market expected to reach about
170,000 units, he expected his group to sell 1,750 houses, against 1,367
last year.
He believed firmer demand for new houses over the next few months would
enable house-builders to remove the incentives - including discounts and
free carpets - they have been offering. Between now and Christmas he
suggested house prices could firm by about 3 per cent as the special
discounts ended. Next year he believed prices could rise by 5 per cent.
After good house sales in August, he said: 'I think we are moving out of
recession, but we are not there yet.'
Mr Geoffrey Higham, chairman of Rugby Group, the UK's third largest cement
manufacturer, is even more cautious about the construction and building
materials sectors.
Although Rugby reported marginally higher first-half pre-tax profits at
Pounds 30.5m, he noted that the construction industry remained depressed and
the group's UK cement sales and profits were both lower in the first six
months.
He also cautioned that year-on-year comparisons could be misleading because
the 1992 first half was relatively buoyant while the second half was 'a
disaster'.
'There appears to be patchy improvement in the UK economy,' he said, but
added that it would be 1994 before the construction industry showed any
growth.
In the meantime some analysts, such as Mr Mark Stockdale of Warburg
Securities, believe the market has already fully discounted the cyclical
recovery.
Most building and construction stocks have risen sharply over the past 12
months. With more building and construction results due this week, Mr
Stockdale said: 'I think it is too late for recovery plays.'
Details, Page 22
