<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Hoover faces probe on transfer of pension funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOOVER UK, the domestic appliances group which launched a disastrous 'free
flights' sales promotion last year, transferred Pounds 28m from its pension
scheme in January, a sum sufficient to cover most of the charges incurred in
connection with the scheme.
The transfer, which netted the company Pounds 16.8m after taxes, was
approved when Mr Bill Foust, the former chairman of Hoover Europe, was
chairman of the pension scheme. Mr Foust was one of two top Hoover
executives sacked in March by US parent company, Maytag, in connection with
the flight offer.
Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP and chairman of the Commons social security
committee, said on the BBC's Watchdog programme yesterday that his committee
planned to investigate the transfer.
Watchdog said the pension fund's annual report described the transfer as 'a
much-needed injection of funds into the company to provide for the growth
and development of Hoover that we all want'. But Mr Field called the
transfer a 'rip-off for pensioners' and 'an abuse'.
Mr Michael Fallon, Hoover's pensions administrator and company secretary,
said the scheme voted to extract cash following a valuation from the
actuaries which showed a surplus of Pounds 100m at March 31, 1991.
'The actuaries advised us that it would be prudent to distribute Pounds 60m
of that to the company and to employees,' he said.
The Dollars 28m transfer to the company was allowed under scheme rules and
was accompanied by an appropriation of Pounds 32.8m to cover enhanced
benefits to current and deferred pensioners, he said.
Hoover has made no contributions to the scheme since December 1986. Most of
the benefit improvements are to current and deferred pensioners who are only
entitled to annual increases of 3 per cent. Those pensions have been uprated
to 95 per cent of their original purchasing power.
Hoover launched its promotion last year, offering free flights to
international destinations to customers who bought any of its products
priced at more than Pounds 120. The scheme backfired when the company was
deluged by customers who claimed the company had failed to make good its
offer.
</TEXT>
