<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Demand for loans remains strong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMAND FOR consumer loans fell slightly in July, but remained at just below
its strongest level for two years.
Central Statistical Office credit figures show that consumers borrowed a net
Pounds 204m in July compared with Pounds 213m in June. The strength of
consumer borrowing supports evidence of rising consumer confidence even
though the figures do not include mortgages and account for only about 15
per cent of consumer debt.
Consumer lending started to revive 10 months ago, suggesting that people
have become more confident about the economic upturn and their personal
financial circumstances.
The latest figures show that increases in loans by building societies and
finance houses were offset by a fall in net lending on bank credit cards.
Consumers borrowed only Pounds 9m more than they paid back on credit cards
in July. This was down from net borrowings of Pounds 64m in June.
Credit-card borrowing has been hesitant since the start of the year
indicating lingering reluctance among consumers to run up big debts.
Net lending by finance houses - mainly hire purchase and loans by retailers
 -was Pounds 189m in July compared with Pounds 150m in the previous month.
Building societies lent a net Pounds 6m compared with a net repayment of
Pounds 1m in the previous month.
The amount of new credit advanced to consumers also fell slightly in July to
Pounds 4.46bn. This was down from Pounds 4.69bn in June. The CSO said the
fall mainly reflected lower advances on credit cards.
But the underlying trend in overall lending remains upwards. In the three
months to July net lending rose to Pounds 535m from Pounds 444m in the
previous quarter.
A separate survey published yesterday by Infolink, the credit information
organisation, reported that consumer confidence was strengthening, with
upturns in July for loans to buy new cars, houses and shop goods.
Meanwhile, the Finance and Leasing Association said consumer confidence was
continuing to rise, with year-on-year gains in all sectors of consumer
credit except those associated with the housing market.
It said, however, that for the first time since the rush to beat the
re-imposition of stamp duty in autumn last year mortgage finance had
increased for two consecutive months.
</TEXT>
