<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Global deal is sought on Maxwell pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MAXWELL Pension Trust, the government-appointed go-between for former
Maxwell company pension schemes and the City, has written to all parties
seeking a 'global settlement' involving up to Pounds 440m in disputed funds.
The trust, chaired by Sir John Cuckney, was set up in June 1992 and by the
end of last year had raised Pounds 6.2m in donations from organisations that
had conducted business with the late Robert Maxwell.
Since then there has been almost no progress in encouraging the return of
contested pension scheme assets from UK organisations and international
investment banks.
Representatives of the schemes said yesterday that if the latest initiative
failed to bring results they were prepared to serve writs against the
investment banks.
An adviser to one of the schemes said: 'This is a last push. If nothing
comes of it over the next two to three months, the writs will fly.'
The letter comes amid growing frustration among pension fund trustees and
administrators.
They had hoped that Sir John would have been able to persuade the banks to
negotiate the return of assets instead of forcing the pensions schemes to
start lengthy and expensive legal proceedings.
