<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / LBC may take licence fight to court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LBC, THE London commercial radio station that is losing both its frequencies
after 20 years' broadcasting to the capital, is seriously considering
seeking a judicial review of the decision.
Mr Matthew Cartisser, LBC executive director, said one possible ground was
that the Radio Authority, the regulatory body for commercial radio in the
UK, had indicated that it did not want a rolling news format because this
was under consideration by the BBC.
Yet London News Radio, the consortium which won both LBC frequencies, is
proposing a rolling news format as well as a discussion station.
Mr Cartisser said: 'We think we have been treated very very shabbily by the
Authority. We rescued LBC (after the collapse of parent Crown
Communications) and saved the Radio Authority from embarrassment.'
LBC chairman Dame Shirley Porter told staff yesterday that lawyers had been
consulted on the possibility of seeking a judicial review. She also revealed
that LBC intended to seek one of the new FM licences for London expected to
be advertised next year.
LBC has launched a petition to try to save its Newstalk and London Talkback
channels. More than 80 per cent of more than 60,000 calls received so far
have been on LBC's side.
The broadcaster is, however, to stop using the airwaves to promote its
cause. This, Mr Cartisser said, was understandable in the emotion of the
lost franchise but it would end.
The company has also taken out newspaper advertisements today which repeat
LBC's pledge to fight on.
</TEXT>
