<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Army suppliers find silver lining in east Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE END of the cold war and cuts in the armed forces have been bad news for
most defence companies but some have found ways of cashing in on the
changes.
Toye, Kenning &amp; Spencer, a long-established Coventry-based manufacturer of
uniforms and insignia, is busy making uniform items for the merged regiments
of the re-organised British army.
And, to prove that every cloud has an embroidered silver lining, it is
seeking to exploit markets in eastern Europe, until recently a no-go area
for British military suppliers.
Mr Philip Frost, managing director, said new business included supplying
badges and buttons to the army's new Royal Logistic Corps, which groups
everyone from drivers to cooks.
Unlike other defence manufacturers, the company had managed to avoid a
decrease in its UK military business, he said.
It was also seeking sales to former Warsaw Pact nations and allies, he said.
It had already sold a uniform package deal to Mozambique, which has changed
its military ranking system from the Soviet to the British style.
The company hoped to increase the 25 per cent of its business devoted to
export. 'We feel we've got an interesting future with the changes that have
occurred,' Mr Frost said.
Also exhibiting at this week's Royal Navy and British Army Equipment
Exhibition in Aldershot is Allmakes Projects, which has a niche business
refitting Russian military trucks.
The company, based in Abingdon, Oxfordshire, has found it can buy trucks for
about Pounds 1,000, and, after fitting Perkins diesel engines, re-sell them
for about Pounds 15,000.
Mr Peter Hands, a director, said it had already sold several hundred,
principally to Angola. It was now looking at opportunities in eastern
Europe.
'There's nobody else doing it that we're aware of,' he said.
</TEXT>
