<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Government backs down on tendering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTMENT of the Environment has decided not to challenge a local
authority which required contractors bidding for street cleaning to
indemnify the council against redundancy costs arising from the tender.
South Lakeland district council in Cumbria decided to include an indemnity
clause in the contract because of the continuing uncertainty about the
rights of staff when public services are contracted out.
Private-sector contractors said yesterday that if the practice of requiring
such indemnities spread it could bring compulsory competitive tendering in
local government almost to a standstill.
One contractor who pulled out of the cleaning tender said yesterday that
providing such indemnities was difficult as the liability was difficult to
assess.
Another contractor described the decision as 'spineless'.
He said: 'It makes a nonsense of compulsory competitive tendering.'
The council asked for the indemnity because it was unsure whether the
contract would be covered by the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of
Employment) 1981 regulations. If the Tupe regulations apply, they protect
the jobs and conditions of the workforce when their jobs are transferred to
another employer.
Lakeland council wanted contractors to provide an indemnity clause in case
the contract for street cleaning subsequently turned out to have been
covered by Tupe.
All four private-sector bidders withdrew from the contest and the contract
was awarded to the council's own workforce.
Although the Department of the Environment normally treats indemnity clauses
as 'anti-competitive behaviour', designed to increase the costs of private
contractors, it has told the council that it proposes to take no further
action.
</TEXT>
