<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / First 125 years of TUC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'WE STUMBLE on,' Norman Willis declared in a speech which was supposed to
sum up the TUC's first 125 years and point to the future.
But, Robert Taylor writes, the delegates sat mostly in suppressed mirth as
journalists wrestled with its meaning.
It was a dismal end to a nine-year reign during which the TUC general
secretary denounced violence on the picket lines during the miners' strike
in 1984, in response to which a noose was dangled in front of his face.
Four years later Mr Willis, as an enthusiastic supporter of the European
Community, brought EC president Jacques Delors to speak to the 1988
Congress, a move that more than any other turned Mrs Thatcher against the
social charter.
Union leaders want a fresh start with a clear sense of direction, after the
government's marginalisation of the unions during Mr Willis's reign. So Mr
John Monks will be making the keynote speech at congress on Wednesday - two
days before he officially takes over from Mr Willis.
</TEXT>
