<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Tecs chief warns against shrinking skills base
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYER-LED Training and Enterprise Councils yesterday warned the
government that any weakening of work-based training would result in many
young people entering dead-end, low-skilled jobs.
Mr John Troth, chairman of the Tec chief executive network, expressed in a
letter to Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, 'the greatest possible
concern' at reports in yesterday's FT that there could be cuts in funding
for Youth Training.
This programme, the centrepiece of work-based training for young people, at
present offers a guaranteed place to any 16-to-19-year-old that wants one.
It is understood that the Department for Education is about to present
proposals to divert the majority of the Pounds 850m a year spent on YT by
the Department of Employment into its own expansion of further education.
Instead of funding going through Tecs to employers and providers of
training, it would be be channelled to colleges through the new quango, the
Further Education Funding Council. Colleges would arrange work experience
where appropriate.
Mr Troth, who pledged Tec support for Mr Hunt's efforts to defend YT, said
the work-based route was an essential option for significant numbers of
young people and it should be employer-led.
He said it encouraged employer commitment to training which in turn led to a
widening of employers' training. It also 'kick-started' the process of
lifelong learning.
</TEXT>
