FT  07 SEP 93 / Italians may stay in Mogadishu
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY SAID it could delay the withdrawal of its troops from Mogadishu, the
Somali capital, for areas to the north, after a United Nations request
yesterday that the troops stay, Reuter reports from Rome.
Defence Minister Fabio Fabbri told Italian state television 'the
(withdrawal) could be delayed, but only by a few days. It will not be
cancelled. Right now we are trying to define the conditions and the timing
of an eventual delay.' Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN secretary-general, had
asked Italy to delay its withdrawal following a weekend ambush in which
seven Nigerian peacekeepers died, a government spokesman said.
The Italians were due to quit Mogadishu at midnight yesterday after a row in
June and July in which they were accused of taking orders from Rome rather
than UN command. Italy is a former colonial power in Somalia.
