<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 93 / Troubled French economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hopes that 1994 will be a year of recovery for the troubled French economy
were strengthened yesterday by confirmation from the government that it
expects growth of 1.4 per cent in gross domestic product next year, write
Alice Rawsthorn and David Buchan in Paris.
However, consumer expenditure is expected to rise more slowly than initially
forecast because of only small reductions in interest rates. By contrast,
the government has upgraded its forecast for exports to 3.2 per cent growth
due to the fall in the franc.
