<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 93 / Multiplication the Transylvanian way: Virginia Marsh finds a
popular Romanian scheme to make money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MORE THAN 2m Romanians 10 per cent of the population
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
have sunk cash
into a pyramid money-multiplying scheme at the Transylvanian town of
Cluj.
The scheme is known as Caritas, although it has no connection with the
international charity of the same name. It takes deposits, with a promise to
pay back eight times the amount in three months.
Tales of 'Caritas millionaires' have spread around Romania, encouraging
thousands of people to descend on Cluj, in Romania's western province, in
the hope of cashing in and hedging against feverish inflation. The scheme
has produced some lei millionaires - in effect, worth over a thousand
dollars.
While most Romanians grapple with soaring prices, declining living standards
and meagre pay, investors deposit a minimum of Lei20,000 (Pounds 15.70),
nearly a third of the average monthly wage. Three months later, Caritas,
which has in the meantime collected from new depositors, pays out eight
times the original investment, less a commission. Many people are leaving
their money in the scheme in the hope of bigger gains to come.
No section of Romanian society appears immune to the lure. Head-scarved
peasant women from the countryside, many clutching bags full of money, wait
their turn in the four-day queue outside the sports hall where Caritas is
based, alongside groups of laughing gypsies. Two young men from Bucharest
furtively count out large bundles of notes. Others, unable to find room in
hotels, sleep in their cars.
All hope it is not too late to benefit from Caritas, even though most say
they know it will eventually collapse like other such schemes, many of which
have sprung up in post-communist Romania and which have various precedents
in other parts of southern Europe.
'Caritas is our only hope of surving the winter,' says a woman who had
travelled 300 kilometres with her elderly father to deposit their monthly
salary and pension in the scheme. 'We can't keep up with the price rises.
Inflation is 260 per cent a year, but we only get 50 per cent interest in
the savings bank.'
The riches Caritas has brought to many in Transylvania have made its
founder, Mr Ioan Stoica, a former bookkeeper, a national hero. He lives
modestly and no-one is able to put a figure on any profits from the scheme.
Others hit by the country's declining economy see Mr Stoica as a Robin Hood
figure. One man says: 'Caritas is an association to give money to the people
and to save them from poverty. I don't know where Stoica gets the money but
he's the only one doing something to help us.'
Caritas has also lifted the popularity of Mr Gheorghe Funar, Cluj's
radically anti-Hungarian mayor and the leader of the Romanian parliament's
largest nationalist party. No formal links between Caritas and the mayor
have been proved but Mr Funar has become its unoffical ambassador.
Diplomats say the scheme looks like a classic money-laundering scam but the
Romanian central government, which since July has been able to levy on
Caritas a new 18 per cent value-added tax, has done little to discourage it.
However, a senior local police officer warned: 'There were near riots in
other towns when similar (schemes) with only a few thousand participants
went bankrupt. I just don't want to think about what will happen here when
we have a whole county and hundreds of thousands of people involved.'
</TEXT>
