<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 93 / Investment body increases activity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WOULD-BE investment regulatory body the Personal Investment Authority is
to launch a campaign to capitalise on the growing support it is receiving.
Although the plan for the PIA got off to a faltering start last September
and it has slipped nearly 12 months behind its original timetable, it has
now received the strong backing of the top investor protection body, the
Securities and Investments Board.
The PIA is expected to release this week further details of how it will
absorb all the members of two existing regulators, the life industry's
Lautro and financial advisers' Fimbra - and also certain investment firms
regulated by Imro, another investment regulator, and others regulated by
SIB.
The objective is to bring all the regulation of retail investment products
and services under the control of a single body. Members will range from the
biggest banks and life assurance companies to the smallest independent
financial advisers.
The plans of the PIA include:
Issuing a formal prospectus by the end of this year, leading in a few months
to recognition by SIB.
Selecting an 18-member board - a reduction on the 30-strong body originally
proposed, but more than the board of 'perhaps 15' recommended by Mr Andrew
Large, SIB chairman.
Authorising several thousand prospective member firms during the early
months of 1994, with the aim of starting operations before the middle of the
year.
Recruiting a chief executive, following a search by headhunters Spencer
Stuart.
</TEXT>
