<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 93 / Gas break-up 'should be rejected'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT should reject the recommendations of the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission for a break-up of British Gas, says the Oxford Institute
for Energy Studies in a report today.
'Other than on purely ideological grounds there appears to be little
justification for seeking greater liberalisation of the UK gas market,' it
says.
A free market would bring benefits to gas producers at the expense of
consumers, it says, and would lead to higher prices because of the
elimination of cross-subsidisation. Dismembering British Gas would threaten
a successful and international company without offering proven benefits.
The Oxford-based think-tank says gas consumers are by and large satisfied
with the performance of the gas industry, and the benefits from a more
competitive market are not clear-cut.
Last month the MMC recommended that British Gas be made to divest its gas
trading operations by 1997. It also urged the removal of its domestic market
monopoly by the year 2002 at the latest.
The Department of Trade and Industry will today publish the complete text of
the report. However, ministers are expected to take several weeks before
deciding whether to accept the recommendations of the report.
Competition and Regulation in the Gas Industry. OIES, 57 Woodstock Road,
Oxford OX2 6FA. Pounds 60.
</TEXT>
