<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 93 / Businesses warn chancellor against harming upturn: FT
writers report on the controversy over the November Budget and gauge the
views of voters and industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Industrial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES ARE warning Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, against raising
taxes in November's Budget. Higher taxes would pose a serious threat to
recovery, it is claimed, weakening consumer demand and undermining
industry's confidence to invest.
The British Retail Consortium, representing 300,000 retail outlets, said it
had written to Mr Clarke urging him not to extend value added tax. 'We are
completely opposed to any extension of the VAT base,' it said.
Retailer WH Smith said it was preparing to launch a co-ordinated lobbying
campaign with publishers and other booksellers to try to persuade Mr Clarke
not to impose VAT on books. The company said: 'We have fought on this issue
on three separate occasions since 1985, so we are used to this battle. But
we have to say the omens look less favourable this time.'
Many retailers fear that an increase in either direct or indirect taxation
could weaken consumer spending. In particular they fear that moving the
Budget to November might pose a threat to the vital Christmas trade. Some
retailers make as much as 90 per cent of their annual profits in the
Christmas and new year period.
Industry bodies such as the Confederation of British Industry and the
Institute of Directors are preparing their Budget submissions for delivery
later this month.
The CBI stopped short of calling for no tax increases. It noted, however,
that the government had already announced tax increases of Pounds 10.5bn
over the next three years in the last Budget. 'We don't want anything that
adds to the burden on business, or endangers recovery,' it said.
Mr John Neill, chief executive of the components group Unipart, pointed out
that the motor industry had received Pounds 1.6bn of help through the
abolition of special car tax. 'It's probably right that the chancellor
should seek to claw some of that back, perhaps through higher petrol duty or
road fund licences,' he said.
But putting up corporate, employment or personal taxation would devastate
Britain's global competitiveness, he said. 'The government must do
everything to cut the national overhead, because otherwise it will drown
British industry.'
Mr John May, managing director of Hambro Countrywide, the estate agency
chain, wanted the chancellor to give priority to spending cuts.
He believed house buyers were particularly sensitive to personal tax
increases in the early stage of a recovery. 'To increase taxes this year
would be very damaging to the recovery,' he said.
</TEXT>
