<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 93 / Clarke to bolster finance initiative
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH Clarke, the chancellor, will this week use his first big speech
after the August holidays to attempt to inject fresh momentum into the
government's flagging private finance initiative.
Addressing the Scottish Confederation of British Industry in Glasgow, Mr
Clarke is expected to announce that a government guide to the initiative -
which is intended to encourage the use of private investment for public
projects - will be published this month. The guide will be aimed primarily
at industry and financial institutions.
He is also expected to foreshadow a possible solution to one of the problems
hampering the sort of private and public-sector partnerships that the
government is trying to nurture - the Treasury requirement for competition
for public-sector contracts.
Such competition can act as a disincentive to companies coming up with
innovative proposals because, once adopted, the proposals must be put out to
competitive tender for implementation. A company devising a project could
find a competitor winning the contract to build it.
One way forward would be to examine the intellectual property rights of
project proposals so companies that develop them could be paid for their
efforts.
The chancellor's comments in the speech, which will also focus on the
Scottish economy, will be eagerly awaited by industrialists and financiers
who are keen to see progress on the private finance initiative.
The initiative was launched with much publicity in last year's Autumn
Statement. But since then the government has announced no significant new
public-sector project involving private finance and the hiatus has caused
concern.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, said recently that the initiative
would be discredited unless 'real holes can be dug in the ground pretty
soon'.
</TEXT>
